  <li><strong>Master the Color-Quality Connection</strong> - The hue of rosé wine directly reflects its production method and grape contact time. Pale salmon-pink rosés (like Provence style) typically come from brief skin contact or saignée method, offering delicate red fruit notes. Deeper coral or cherry-tinted rosés often use direct press or longer maceration, delivering more intensity. Avoid rosés with brown or orange tinges—these indicate oxidation or over-aging, common mistakes in rosé production.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at the Perfect 50-55°F Sweet Spot</strong> - Rosé wine demands precise temperature control between 50-55°F (10-13°C)—warmer than white wine but cooler than red. This temperature preserves the wine's fresh acidity while allowing subtle red fruit aromatics to emerge. Too cold (below 45°F) and you'll mute the wine's complexity; too warm (above 60°F) and the alcohol becomes prominent, masking rosé's characteristic elegance. Use an ice bucket with half ice, half water for 15 minutes to achieve ideal serving temperature.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip the Decanter—Rosé Needs Immediate Enjoyment</strong> - Unlike red wines, rosé should never be decanted or allowed to breathe extensively. The wine's primary charm lies in its fresh, primary fruit aromatics and crisp acidity, which dissipate quickly upon exposure to air. Pour rosé directly from bottle to glass, and consume within 2-3 hours of opening. The exception: very young, high-quality rosés from producers like Domaine Tempier may benefit from 15 minutes of gentle aeration to soften any residual tannins.</li>

