<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Most rosé wines are crafted for immediate enjoyment, but understanding their aging potential can enhance your drinking experience. The majority of rosés, including Provence classics and New World styles, reach their peak within <strong>1-3 years of vintage</strong>, when their bright acidity and fresh fruit flavors remain vibrant.</p>

<h3>Quality Levels and Aging Potential</h3>

<p>Entry-level rosés should be consumed within 18 months, while premium bottlings from producers like Domaine Tempier or Château d'Esclans can evolve beautifully for 3-5 years. <strong>Champagne rosé and quality Crémant rosé</strong> can age gracefully for 5-10 years, developing toasty complexity while maintaining their elegant structure.</p>

<h3>How Rosé Evolves</h3>

<p>As rosé ages, the initial strawberry and citrus notes gradually shift toward more complex flavors of dried herbs, white pepper, and subtle nuttiness. The wine's vibrant pink hue naturally fades to salmon or onion-skin tones—this is normal evolution, not spoilage. Well-made rosés with higher acidity, like those from Sancerre or Bandol, develop <strong>mineral complexity</strong> while retaining freshness.</p>

<h3>Proper Storage Requirements</h3>

<p>Store rosé at a consistent <strong>50-55°F (10-13°C)</strong> with 70% humidity. Keep bottles on their side to maintain cork moisture, away from direct light and vibration. Unlike reds, rosés are particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations, which can accelerate unwanted oxidation.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>

<p>Properly aged rosé maintains clean aromatics with evolved complexity. Warning signs of spoilage include: brown or orange discoloration beyond normal evolution, vinegar-like aromas, or flat, lifeless flavors. A slight color fade is expected, but the wine should still smell fresh and taste balanced, even as primary fruit gives way to tertiary development.</p>

