    <p class="text-gray-700">Dry rosé wines contain less than 4 grams of residual sugar per liter and showcase crisp, mineral-driven flavors with bright acidity. Sweet rosé wines, often labeled as "off-dry" or "demi-sec," contain 12-45 grams of residual sugar per liter and display softer, fruit-forward characteristics. The majority of premium rosé wines from Provence, Loire Valley, and quality producers worldwide are made in the dry style, while sweeter versions are more common in commercial American brands.</p>
