  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the most common mistakes when buying rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is choosing rosé based on color intensity, assuming darker equals better or more flavorful—when actually, the best rosé often displays pale salmon or onion-skin hues. Another error is buying rosé that's more than two years old unless it's specifically a premium age-worthy style. Many consumers also overlook the vintage date entirely, not realizing that rosé's charm lies in its youthful freshness and bright acidity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is rosé wine a good choice for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé is an excellent entry point for new wine drinkers because it bridges the gap between white and red wines with moderate complexity and food-friendly acidity. The approachable fruit flavors—strawberry, watermelon, and citrus—are easily recognizable, while the wine's versatility with food helps build confidence in pairing. Quality dry rosé also teaches beginners to appreciate balance and finesse over power, establishing a foundation for exploring other wine styles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best alternatives to expensive Provence rosé?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Spanish rosé from Navarra offers similar pale color and mineral-driven character at half the price of Provence. Italian rosato from Puglia or Marche provides excellent value with slightly more body and fruit intensity. For domestic options, rosé from Virginia's Monticello AVA or Oregon's Willamette Valley delivers comparable elegance and food-pairing versatility without the premium markup of imported French wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long does an opened bottle of rosé wine stay fresh?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">An opened bottle of rosé will maintain its best qualities for 3-5 days when stored in the refrigerator with a proper wine stopper or vacuum seal. The wine's bright acidity and lower tannin structure make it more susceptible to oxidation than red wines, so it's best consumed sooner rather than later. After the fifth day, while still safe to drink, the wine will lose its characteristic freshness and vibrant fruit flavors that make rosé so appealing.</p>
  </div>
